  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good sources for free instrumental music to use in video tutorials?",
  "response": "There are several great sources for free instrumental music that you can use in video tutorials. Here are some options to consider:\n\n1. **YouTube Audio Library**: This is an extensive collection of free music and sound effects provided by YouTube. You can filter by genre, mood, and duration to find suitable tracks.\n\n2. **Free Music Archive (FMA)**: FMA offers a wide range of high-quality, free music in various genres. Just be sure to check the licensing for each track, as some may have specific attribution requirements.\n\n3. **Incompetech**: Created by composer Kevin MacLeod, Incompetech offers a large selection of royalty-free music. Tracks are categorized by genre, mood, and length, making it easy to find what you need. Most tracks require attribution.\n\n4. **Bensound**: Bensound provides a variety of free music tracks, particularly suitable for video projects. While you can use the music for free under certain conditions (attribution), paid licenses are also available for broader usage.\n\n5. **ccMixter**: This platform features a collaborative community of musicians who share their work under Creative Commons licenses. You can find a range of instrumental music that can be used for free, often with attribution.\n\n6. **SoundCloud**: Some creators on SoundCloud offer their tracks under Creative Commons licenses, allowing for free use in projects. Be sure to filter for results that are labeled for reuse.\n\n7. **Musopen**: Musopen provides free access to classical music recordings, sheet music, and educational materials. It's a great source for high-quality instrumental pieces that are in the public domain.\n\n8. **Jamendo**: Jamendo offers a large selection of free music by independent artists, available for personal and educational use. Make sure to check the licensing for each track.\n\n9. **Freesound**: While primarily a sound effects repository, Freesound also has a collection of musical tracks. Most of the content is shared under Creative Commons licenses.\n\n10. **Audionautix**: Run by composer Jason Shaw, Audionautix features a variety of royalty-free music that can be used in projects without charge, as long as you provide attribution.\n\nRemember to always check the licensing agreements for each source and track to ensure compliance with their usage policies.",
